ir</i>) ‘plain, field’, especially a battlefield (Irish <i>blár</i>). There were families of this name in the Middle Ages taking their names from any of the places called Blair in Dysart parish Fife, Dalry parish Ayrshire, and Blairgowrie in Perthshire.","Americanized form of French   Belair   and   Blais  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Belair","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Lucien, Aime, Auguste, Aurele, Carmelle, Normand, Raoul, Rolande.","French (also <b>Bélair</b>): habitational name from Belair, Bélair or (Le) Bel-Air, names of several places in various parts of France, meaning literally ‘beautiful place’. Compare   Belaire  ,   Bellair  ,   Bellaire  , and   Blair  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Blair of that Ilk was born about 1439, in Ayrshire, Scotland, his father, Hugh Blair of that Ilk, 8th Lord of Blair, was 27 and his mother, Martha Ogston, was 27. He married Lady Marion MacMorran about 1454, in Ayrshire, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1513, in Ayrshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 75."},"et":{"about 1439–1513":"umbes 1439–1513","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1439–1513":"1439–1513","1440–Female":"1440–Surnud","1457–1513":"1457–1513","1478–1530":"1478–1530","1480–1529":"1480–1529","1413–1462":"1413–1462","1413–Female":"1413–Surnud","1462":"1462","1440":"1440","1480":"1480","1513":"1513","about 1439":"umbes 1439","1413":"1413","1457":"1457","1478":"1478","about 1429":"umbes 1429","19 January 1457":"19. jaanuar 1457","before December 1462":"enne detsembrit 1462","1530":"1530","1430":"1430","about 1454":"umbes 1454","1529":"1529","1439":"1439","Ayrshire, Kingdo